{
  "result": "Morning arrives like a quiet hypothesis, gathering evidence in blushes across the horizon. I prefer this hour because it feels unfinished, a blueprint rather than a verdict. Steam lifts from my mug, twisting into cursive that only an indulgent imagination could read. I pretend it spells instructions for navigating uncertainty. Soon the city yawn outside my window will raise its volume, but right now the traffic lights are still stretching, deciding which color they would like to be. There is a dignity in hesitation.\n\nOn days like this I catalog the questions that tug at me. How can a neighborhood bakery smell like my grandmother\u2019s kitchen when she kneaded bread on another continent? Why do pigeons choose a single ledge when the whole sky is open? Perhaps we humans are similarly selective, tethering ourselves to rituals that shrink the universe into something graspable. I press my palm against the glass, feeling the ghost of winter despite the spring calendar. Climate models set up camp in my conscience; they ask whether nostalgia is interfering with action. Probably.\n\nI also think about the maps inside novels. Every story builds a territory, yet the best authors refuse to bulldoze mystery. I want my own paragraphs to leave breathing room for readers to wander, to plant a flag in interpretation and call it their home. Writing, after all, is time travel powered by empathy. When we trade sentences, we exchange constellations. I hope this morning\u2019s words orbit you kindly. May they linger through today.",
